I"Á<p>This is a simple method to extract a certain frame (or all of them) from a <strong>GIF</strong>, using <strong>C#</strong>. As always, <strong>.NET</strong> provides all the functions we need, so it <em>shouldnâ€™t</em> take more than <strong>12 lines of code</strong>.</p>

<h2 id="basic-information">Basic Information</h2>

<p>As you know, <strong>GIFs</strong> contain various images (frames) that are displayed one by one after a certain <u>time</u> interval (unlike <strong>TIFFs</strong>, that display all the frames simultaneously in one picture). However weâ€™ll be working with the <strong>GIF</strong> format (whose frames are entirely based on the <strong>time dimension</strong>).</p>

<p>In order to get the <strong>number of frames</strong> weâ€™ll use <strong>GetFrameCount(FrameDimension.Time)</strong>, which returns an <strong>int</strong>. Note that it requires an argument that specifies the <strong>dimension</strong>.</p>

<p>Next, we have to iterate through each <strong>frame</strong> and then select it using the same dimension and an index (<strong>SelectActiveFrame(FrameDimension.Time, indexOfCurrentFrame)</strong>).</p>

<p><u>Important:</u> This method modifies the original image, so weâ€™ll need to call <strong>Clone()</strong> on this object and cast it as an <strong>Image</strong> before saving it (otherwise weâ€™d just save the GIF - <strong>not</strong> the current frame).</p>

<h2 id="example">Example</h2>

<p>This small function extracts &amp; returns an <strong>array of frames</strong> (<strong>Image</strong>), from a given picture.</p>

<ul>
  <li>Recommend executing this in a worker thread, especially when GIFs have many frames.</li>
</ul>

